>October 27th
>Your friends are a little TOO into the Halloween spirit this year
>Apart from all the parties they want to drag you to, they decide they want to try a little urban exploration
>Specifically, at the abandoned “Freak Factory”
>A haunted house attraction long since abandoned for being too expensive to keep even the dimmest of lights on
>Not to mention the employee actors got a little too “grabby” and faced more than a handful of lawsuits
>So the building was shut down and the land remains untouched
>Naturally, it’s an extremely popular spot for trespassers and risk takers to invade
>This is especially true because of how many supposed accounts of ghosts and monsters there have been from those who dared enter
>The stories got so widespread that the police have since added the building to their more frequent patrol routes
>You’re a little more worried about the legal consequences than you are about running into a vampire or mummy or something
>They won’t admit it, but your friends feel the same way
>When you asked why you weren’t doing this on Halloween night, they scoffed at you
>”There’s going to be more pigs than any other night, because everyone else is going to have the same idea.”
>Your friend Haywood is the instigator and the ringleader
>This whole thing is his doing to begin with
>Your other friend, nicknamed “Sticks”, pretty much goes where he’s told
>Like you in most ways, but not as confident in objecting
>The sun has just set when the three of you arrive at Freak Factory
>You hop the rusted turnstiles and make your way to the boarded up doors
>The barricades are just for show, and the place is surprisingly unlocked
>Sticks is pissing himself before you even get inside
>At this point your biggest fear is running into other people
>Hobos, other intruders, actual serial killers
>The main foyer branches off in several directions, each one for a different type of experience
>Spooky mansion, torture dungeon, murderous restaurant (annoyingly popular in recent years), witch-filled woods...
>Even a few places that aren’t supposed to be as terrifying, like the small theater for those who chicken out of the main thrills, are given an ominous atmosphere because of the place’s derelict condition
>Haywood picks the mansion first, keeping a few steps ahead but making frequent checks to see if you’re still following
>So far so good
>You honestly might not have had the nerve to do this alone, but with someone like Sticks around to be the biggest coward it somehow eases things up a bit
>As you delve deeper, you realize the scare factor of the attraction is almost non-existent with everything shut off
>You even have to suppress a yawn just do you don’t inhale all the dust
>BANG
>The sound of a slamming door echoes from the direction you came
>Sticks covers his ears and even Haywood lets a startled “eek”
>”Mmm...who do we have tonight?”
>There’s a sultry, but rough female voice all around you
>Like a starlet who yelled herself hoarse, or a strangled opera singer
>”Just the three of you? That’s less than usual. Oh well. Fewer bodies they’ll come looking for....”
>You hear the solid THUD of something drop to the creaking floorboards
>And the clacking of its claws on the scratched wood
>And it’s getting closer
>There’s your cue to leave!
>The three of you run off in different directions at first, but you and Sticks pull around to follow Haywood
>Your leader is already several paces ahead in a mad dash
>The rooms seem to have no particular orientation or sense of scale
>Just endless halls and cluttered set pieces
>It IS a horror attraction after all, and not just someone’s livable abode
>Speaking of which...
>The props and animatronics come to life, blocking your route and bouncing you around with their distorted scares and grasping appendages
>You and Sticks struggle through the obstacle course
>When you turn a corner you see Haywood trying to pull open a door
>Before you can reach him it swings Haywood into a false, rotating wall
>He screams, tumbling out of sight
>There’s no sign of a trap door ever being there
>The mocking laughter of the hidden voice keeps you running forward
>Barreling out of the haunted mansion dumps you two in a new section of the building that looks like an indoor forest
>The acoustics of the voice are even more unsettling as they bounce off the hollow trees
>”The boy fell over with a single puff, out cold. That’s...dissatisfying. I hope the two of you make up for what a bore he was.”
>The forest is even harder to navigate with its lack of a clear path
>You and Sticks eventually reach a chasm with several rickety rope bridges strung over a lightless void
>The direction you came from starts disappearing into shadow
>The two of you take different bridges, hoping the weight won’t be too much just for a single body
>It squeaks and sways as you cross
>There’s a snapping noise, and Sticks is gone with a yelp
>”Well, that one didn’t have much to give either. He gave faster than the bridge did! HAHAHA!”
>You reach solid land and press onward
>The rest of the bridges snap and crack at your heels
>”Just...one...left....”
>You make it to a cabin; really just an entrance leading to a new horror backdrop
>But it looks believable, and you barely have time to shut the wooden door before you hear pounding from the other side
>The door rattles fiercely on its hinges
>”Let me in...let me in....” she sings
>None of the rooms lead anywhere
>Except the stairs to the basement
>Fuck
